  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA41-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pirivuṇarttappaṭṭu āṟṟāḷāya (ET: piriviṉkaṇ) talaimakaḷait (EV: talaimakaṉait; ET: talaimakaṭkut) tōḻi ulakiyal kūṟi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforted HER, who did not have the strength after being informed about the separation, by speaking about the nature of the world.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA41">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            paiṅkaṇ yāṉaip parūuttā ḷutaitta</l>
<l>            veṇpuṟak kaḷari viṭunī ṟāṭic</l>
<l>            curaṉmutal varuntiya varuttam paipayap</l>
<l>            pāram viciṟu kūvaliṟ ṟaṇiyu</l>
<l>            neṭuñcēṭ ceṉṟu varuntuvar mātō </l>
<l>            velli vanta nallicai viruntiṟkuk</l>
<l>            kiḷariḻai yarivai neytuḻan taṭṭa</l>
<l>            viḷarū ṉaṟumpukai yeṟinta neṟṟic</l>
<l>            ciṟunuṇ palviyar poṟitta</l>
<l>            kuṟunaṭaik kūṭṭam vēṇṭu vōrē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

<l>Will he not suffer,</l>
<l rend="indent4">going the long distance,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the green-eyed elephant, having bathed in the loose</l>
<l rend="indent">dust<note place="foot">Literally: “ashes”; it is impossible to tell whether the text is already playing on the later religious associations of besmearing oneself with sacred ashes.</note> of saline soil with white outside kicked up by [his] big foot,</l>
<l rend="indent2">gently alleviates the suffering experienced</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the desert in the well sprinkling the rocks?</l>
<l>– he who wants union with [her of] short steps,</l>
<l rend="indent2">bespattered with perspiration in many little fine [drops],</l>
<l rend="indent2">[her] front stung by the fragrant smoke of whitening meat,</l>
<l rend="indent">stirred [and] cooked in ghee, the young woman of shining jewels</l>
<l rend="indent3">for the musical feast<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nal icai viruntu</term>: I don’t take this to refer to the topos of HER cooking for a guest, but for an allusion, made by the confidante to delay HIS departure, to the beauty of daily home life when SHE will cook for HIM in the evening before they spend the night together.</note> when night comes.</l>
      </lg>
